paragraph: Arnaud Beauville (born 10 May 1947) is a French mathematician, whose research interest is algebraic geometry.
paragraph: Beauville earned his doctorate from Paris Diderot University in 1977, with a thesis regarding Prym varieties and the Schottky problem, under supervision of Jean-Louis Verdier.
paragraph: He has been a professor at the Université Paris-Sud, then Director of the Mathematics Department at the École Normale Supérieure. He is currently Professor emeritus at the Université de Nice Sophia-Antipolis.
paragraph: Beauville was a visiting scholar at the Institute for Advanced Study in the summer of 1982. He was an invited speaker at the International Congress of Mathematicians in 1986 at Berkeley. He was a member of Bourbaki. He has had 25 Ph.D. students, among them Claire Voisin, Olivier Debarre, Yves Laszlo.
paragraph: In 2012 he became a fellow of the American Mathematical Society.

Summary: 
Arnaud Beauville (born May 10, 1947, in Boulogne-Billancourt, Paris, France) is a prominent French mathematician specializing in algebraic geometry. He obtained his doctorate from Paris Diderot University in 1977 under the supervision of Jean-Louis Verdier, completing a thesis on Prym varieties and the Schottky problem. Over his scientific career, he has been affiliated with the University of Angers, Université Paris-Sud, École Normale Supérieure (where he directed the Mathematics Department), and Université de Nice Sophia-Antipolis (currently Professor emeritus). Notable milestones include a 1982 visiting scholarship at the Institute for Advanced Study, speaking at the 1986 International Congress of Mathematicians, membership in the Bourbaki group, and becoming an American Mathematical Society fellow in 2012. He has advised 25 Ph.D. students, including notable mathematicians like Claire Voisin, Olivier Debarre, and Yves Laszlo. This comprehensive profile can be used to cross-reference against specific clues.
