[visit] The useful information from visiting https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_twenty-first_problem for user goal 'Go directly to the Wikipedia article for Hilbert's twenty-first problem' as follows: 

Evidence in page: 
The twenty-first problem of the 23 Hilbert problems, from the celebrated list put forth in 1900 by David Hilbert, concerns the existence of a certain class of linear differential equations with specified singular points and monodromic group.

In the theory of linear differential equations with one independent variable z, I wish to indicate an important problem one which very likely Riemann himself may have had in mind. This problem is as follows: To show that there always exists a linear differential equation of the Fuchsian class, with given singular points and monodromic group.

In fact it is more appropriate to speak not about differential equations but about linear systems of differential equations: in order to realise any monodromy by a differential equation one has to admit, in general, the presence of additional apparent singularities... The question is whether the mapping from these Fuchsian equations to classes of representations is surjective.

The history of proofs involving a single complex variable is complicated. Josip Plemelj published a solution in 1908. This work was for a long time accepted as a definitive solution... Plemelj's claim that the system can be made Fuchsian at the last point as well is wrong, unless the monodromy is diagonalizable there. Indeed Andrey A. Bolibrukh (1990) found a counterexample to Plemelj's statement. This is commonly viewed as providing a counterexample to the precise question Hilbert had in mind; Bolibrukh showed that for a given pole configuration certain monodromy groups can be realised by regular, but not by Fuchsian systems.

Summary: 
Hilbert's twenty-first problem, proposed in 1900, asks whether there always exists a linear differential equation of the Fuchsian class with given singular points and a prescribed monodromic group. While Josip Plemelj published what was thought to be a definitive solution in 1908, Andrey A. Bolibrukh discovered a counterexample in 1990, demonstrating that certain monodromy groups can be realized by regular systems, but not by Fuchsian ones. This established a negative resolution to Hilbert's precise question, though related bijective correspondences, known as Riemann–Hilbert correspondences, have since been developed.
