Institutions Leningrad University Linköping University Ohio State University University of Liverpool
Vladimir Gilelevich Maz'ya... is a Russian-born Swedish mathematician, hailed as "one of the most distinguished analysts of our time" and as "an outstanding mathematician of worldwide reputation", who strongly influenced the development of mathematical analysis and the theory of partial differential equations.
Vladimir Maz'ya was born on 31 December 1937 in a Jewish family. His father died in December 1941 at the World War II front, and all four grandparents died during the siege of Leningrad. His mother, a state accountant, chose to not remarry and dedicated her life to him...
In 1955, at the age of 18, Maz'ya entered the Mathematics and Mechanics Department of Leningrad University. ... he attracted the attention of Solomon Mikhlin who invited him at his home, thus starting their lifelong friendship...
From 1960 up to 1986, he worked as a "research fellow" at the Research Institute of Mathematics and Mechanics of Leningrad University (RIMM)... From 1968 to 1978 he taught at the Leningrad Shipbuilding Institute, where he was awarded the title of "professor" in 1976. From 1986 to 1990 he worked to the Leningrad Section of the Blagonravov Research Institute of Mechanical Engineering of the USSR Academy of Sciences...
In 1978 he married Tatyana Shaposhnikova... In 1990, they left the URSS for Sweden, where Prof. Maz'ya obtained the Swedish citizenship and started to work at Linköping University. Currently, he is honorary Senior Fellow of Liverpool University and Professor Emeritus at Linköping University.
The summary of the Candidate of Sciences thesis of Aben Khvoles, one of the doctoral students of Vladimir Maz'ya...
Publications and conferences and dedicated to Vladimir Maz'ya
"Analysis, PDEs and Applications, Conference on the occasion of the 70th birthday of Vladimir Maz'ya"...
Harmonic Analysis and PDE. International Conference in honor of Vladimir Maz'ya...
Workshop on Sobolev Spaces and Partial Differential Equations In honour of V. Maz'ya on the occasion of his 80th birthday...
Around the research of Vladimir Maz'ya. I. Function spaces... II. Partial Differential Equations... III. Analysis and applications spaces

Summary: 
Vladimir Gilelevich Mazya is a prominent Russian-born Swedish mathematician born on December 31, 1937, in Leningrad. He is globally recognized for his profound impact on mathematical analysis, partial differential equations, and Sobolev spaces. He studied at Leningrad University, developed a lifelong friendship with mentor Solomon Mikhlin, and guided doctoral students like Aben Khvoles. His extensive academic career features positions at Leningrad University, the Leningrad Shipbuilding Institute, Linköping University in Sweden (where he relocated in 1990 and gained citizenship), and the University of Liverpool. Married to fellow mathematician Tatyana Shaposhnikova, Mazya's achievements have earned him prestigious awards, including the Humboldt Prize, Celsius Gold Medal, and Senior Whitehead Prize. His legacy is further cemented by numerous international conferences and multi-volume publications dedicated to honoring his research on his 70th, 75th, and 80th birthdays. This comprehensive profile provides robust data for cross-referencing with the user's clues.
