Roman Valeryevich Mikhailov (Russian: Роман Валерьевич Михайлов; born 2 October 1978) is a Russian mathematician, writer, and film and theatre director. He holds a Doctor of Sciences degree in physics and mathematics and is a professor of the Russian Academy of Sciences. Mikhailov is the author of more than 60 scientific publications and a monograph in algebra and topology, and is also a novelist and independent filmmaker.

He is a specialist in homological algebra, homotopy theory, and group theory. He was an invited speaker at the 7th European Congress of Mathematics (2016) and at the International Congress of Mathematicians (2022). In 2021, he received the Andrei Bely Prize for prose.

Mikhailov's research interests include homological and homotopical algebra, algebraic K-theory, group theory, group rings, and category theory. Together with Laurent Bartholdi, Mikhailov solved the dimension subgroup problem... Mikhailov introduced several concepts in group theory and homotopy theory, including homotopy patterns...

Mikhailov is the author of several experimental novels and short-story collections, including Ravinagar (2016), The Beautiful Night of All People (2017), Berries (2020), and Wait for Summer and See What Happens (2021).

Mikhailov made his directorial film debut with A Fairy Tale for the Old (2022), co-directed with actor Fyodor Lavrov; the film won the main prize at the Spirit of Fire Film Festival.

Summary: 
Roman Valeryevich Mikhaylov (born October 2, 1978) is a Russian mathematician, writer, film and theatre director, and screenwriter. Educated at Moscow State University, he holds a Doctor of Sciences degree and was a professor at the Russian Academy of Sciences, specializing in homological algebra, homotopy theory, and group theory. He is known for solving the dimension subgroup problem and introducing concepts like homotopy patterns. Outside of mathematics, he has authored experimental prose—winning the 2021 Andrei Bely Prize—and directed independent films, including his debut 'A Fairy Tale for the Old', which won the Grand Prize at the Spirit of Fire Film Festival.
