Alexander Merkurjev (born September 25, 1955, in Saint Petersburg, USSR) is a renowned Russian-American mathematician and professor at the University of California, Los Angeles. He obtained his education from Leningrad University. Merkurjev has made major contributions to the field of algebra, focusing on algebraic groups, quadratic forms, Galois cohomology, algebraic K-theory, and central simple algebras. He is particularly known for the Merkurjev–Suslin theorem and his fundamental contributions to the notion of essential dimension. Throughout his career, he has received several prestigious awards, including the Petersburg Mathematical Society Prize (1982), the Humboldt Prize (1995), and the Cole Prize in Algebra (2012).
