Summary: 
Vladimir Alexandrovich Voevodsky (June 4, 1966 – September 30, 2017) was an influential Russian-American mathematician. After receiving his Ph.D. from Harvard University in 1992 under the advisement of David Kazhdan, he went on to make significant contributions at the intersection of algebraic geometry and algebraic topology. He is best known for developing a homotopy theory for algebraic varieties and formulating motivic cohomology, achievements that earned him the prestigious Fields Medal in 2002. He also successfully proved the Milnor and motivic Bloch-Kato conjectures and significantly advanced the univalent foundations of mathematics and homotopy type theory. Voevodsky served as a professor at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton from 2002 until his passing in 2017.
