Born Vladimir Alexandrovich Voevodsky 4 June 1966 Moscow, Soviet Union
Died 30 September 2017 (aged 51) Princeton, New Jersey, United States
Alma mater Moscow State University Harvard University
Awards Fields Medal (2002)
Institutions Institute for Advanced Study
Vladimir Alexandrovich Voevodsky... was a Russian-American mathematician. His work in developing a homotopy theory for algebraic varieties and formulating motivic cohomology led to the award of a Fields Medal in 2002. He is also known for the proof of the Milnor conjecture and motivic Bloch–Kato conjectures and for the univalent foundations of mathematics and homotopy type theory.
Voevodsky attended Moscow State University for a while, but was expelled without a diploma for refusing to attend classes and failing academically. He received his Ph.D. in mathematics from Harvard University in 1992 after being recommended without even applying and without a formal college degree, following several independent publications; he was advised there by David Kazhdan.
From 2002, Voevodsky was a professor at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.

Summary: 
Vladimir Alexandrovich Voevodsky (June 4, 1966 – September 30, 2017) was a highly influential Russian-American mathematician. Despite being expelled from Moscow State University, he was admitted to Harvard University, where he earned his Ph.D. in 1992 without a formal college degree, guided by his independent publications. He is best known for his groundbreaking work in developing homotopy theory for algebraic varieties and formulating motivic cohomology, achievements that earned him the Fields Medal in 2002. His contributions also include proofs of the Milnor and Bloch–Kato conjectures, as well as pioneering the univalent foundations of mathematics and homotopy type theory. Since 2002, he served as a professor at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, until his death from an aneurysm at the age of 51.
