Evidence in page: 
Ivan Fesenko is a mathematician working in number theory and its interaction with other areas of modern mathematics. He was born in St Petersburg, Russia. Fesenko was educated at St. Petersburg State University where he was awarded a PhD in 1987. His doctoral advisors were Sergei Vostokov and Alexander Merkurjev, and his notable doctoral students include Caucher Birkar. After continuing at St. Petersburg State University as assistant and associate professor, he became professor in pure mathematics at the University of Nottingham in the UK. He moved to Westlake University in China as a distinguished professor of mathematics in 2023. Fesenko was awarded the Prize of the Petersburg Mathematical Society in 1992. He contributed to several areas of number theory such as class field theory and its generalizations, explicit formulas for the generalized Hilbert symbol on local fields and higher local field, higher class field theory, p-class field theory, arithmetic noncommutative local class field theory. He coauthored a textbook on local fields and a volume on higher local fields. Fesenko discovered a higher Haar measure and integration on various higher local and adelic objects. He pioneered the study of zeta functions in higher dimensions by developing his theory of higher adelic zeta integrals. He generalized the Iwasawa-Tate theory from 1-dimensional global fields to 2-dimensional arithmetic surfaces. His theory led to developments in the study of functional equation and meromorphic continuation of the Hasse zeta function, applications to the generalized Riemann hypothesis, and relations between the arithmetic and analytic ranks of an elliptic curve over a global field (Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture). Fesenko played an active role in organizing the study of inter-universal Teichmüller theory (IUT) of Shinichi Mochizuki, authoring surveys and co-organizing international workshops on the topic.

Summary: 
Ivan Fesenko is a Russian-born mathematician recognized for his extensive work in number theory. He earned his PhD from St. Petersburg State University in 1987, where he began his academic career before becoming a professor at the University of Nottingham and later a distinguished professor at Westlake University in China (2023). His prominent research contributions include advancements in class field theory, the introduction of a higher Haar measure, the pioneering of higher adelic zeta integrals for studying zeta functions in higher dimensions, and generalizations of the Iwasawa-Tate theory. His work has applications to the generalized Riemann hypothesis and the Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture. Additionally, he has been a key figure in organizing and studying Shinichi Mochizuki's inter-universal Teichmüller theory. He was awarded the Petersburg Mathematical Society Prize in 1992.
