Akif Jafar Hajiyev (Azerbaijani: Akif Cəfər oğlu Hacıyev, 8 December 1937 – 3 February 2015) was an Azerbaijani mathematician. He served as the vice-president of the Azerbaijan National Academy of Sciences from 2013 until his death. From 2004 to 2013, he was the director of the Institute of Mathematics and Mechanics of the National Academy of Sciences. He authored four books, in addition to numerous papers. By presidential decree, he was awarded the "Order of Glory" in 2004 and "Honored Worker of Science" in 2005. He became the president of the Azerbaijan Mathematical Society in 2010. A native of Baku, Hajiyev was best known for his work in the theory of multidimensional singular integrals.

Summary: 
Akif Jafar Hajiyev (December 8, 1937 – February 3, 2015) was an Azerbaijani mathematician born in Baku. He held a Doctor of Physical and Mathematical Sciences degree. Professionally, he served as the vice-president of the Azerbaijan National Academy of Sciences (2013-2015), director of the Institute of Mathematics and Mechanics (2004-2013), and president of the Azerbaijan Mathematical Society (from 2010). He authored four books and numerous papers, and was best known for his work in the theory of multidimensional singular integrals. He received the "Order of Glory" in 2004 and was named an "Honored Worker of Science" in 2005.
