Klavdiya Yakovlevna Latysheva (born 14 March 1897, Kyiv, Russian Empire – 11 May 1956, Kyiv, Ukrainian SSR, Soviet Union) was a Soviet mathematician known for her contributions to the theory of differential equations, electrodynamics and probability. She was honoured with the Order of Lenin and the Medal "For Valiant Labour in the Great Patriotic War 1941–1945". She was the first Ukrainian woman to obtain a doctorate in the mathematical and physical sciences, with her dissertation on approximate solutions of linear differential equations with singular coefficients (1936). Latysheva was an organiser of the first All-Ukrainian Mathematical Olympiad in 1936. Latysheva developed an effective method for the construction of solutions of linear ordinary differential equations around regular and irregular points by expanding on Poincaré's concept of rank and L. Tome's concept of anti-rank. This is now known as the Frobenius-Latysheva method.

Summary: 
Klavdiya Latysheva (1897–1956) was a prominent Soviet mathematician recognized for her work in differential equations, electrodynamics, and probability. Notably, she was the first Ukrainian woman to receive a doctorate in mathematical and physical sciences. She is best known for developing the Frobenius-Latysheva method, which helps construct solutions for linear ordinary differential equations. She also co-organized the first All-Ukrainian Mathematical Olympiad in 1936 and was honored with the Order of Lenin for her scientific contributions.
