Evidence in page: 
Dmitry Yevgenyevich Okhotsimsky (26 February 1921 – 18 December 2005) was a Soviet and Russian space scientist and engineer in the former Soviet space program who pioneered the studies in robotics, controls, and space ballistics. He wrote fundamental works in applied celestial mechanics, spaceflight dynamics and robotics. Okhotsimsky was born and lived his whole life in Moscow. In 1949 he joined the Mathematical Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, where was working in the department of Applied Mathematics led by Mstislav Keldysh... the group of Okhotsimsky became a department in this institute, which he was leading until his death. Okhotsimsky contributed to the planning of multiple space missions including launches to Moon, Mars and Venus. His analysis of the first failed docking attempts on Soyuz spacecraft helped to quickly find a reason of mechanical instability and develop successful docking techniques... He developed a concept of a dual-entry aerodynamically controlled landing algorithm of a spacecraft... Okhotsimsky's team... did analysis and optimization of multi-stage rocket designs. This led directly to the design of the R-7 missile and the exact proportions of its strap-on booster stages. In the middle of the 1970s Okhotsimsky became interested in robotics, especially in the modeling and control of insect-like walking. A few successful models of 6-legged walking robots were created... He was a Member of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Academician since 1991, and received numerous awards including the Lenin Prize (1957), Hero of Socialist Labour (1961), and the USSR State Prize (1970). Minor planet 8062 was named Okhotsymskij in his honor.

Summary: 
Dmitry Yevgenyevich Okhotsimsky (1921–2005) was a prominent Soviet and Russian space scientist and engineer. Spending his career primarily at the Keldysh Institute of Applied Mathematics, he played a crucial role in the Soviet space program, pioneering studies in space ballistics, celestial mechanics, and spaceflight dynamics. His major contributions include the planning of missions to the Moon, Mars, and Venus, the optimization of multi-stage rocket designs that led to the R-7 missile, and the development of aerodynamically controlled spacecraft landing algorithms. In his later career, he focused on robotics, developing successful six-legged walking robots. An Academician of the Russian Academy of Sciences, his significant achievements were recognized with prestigious honors, including the Lenin Prize, the title of Hero of Socialist Labour, and having a minor planet named after him.
