Pyotr Leonidovich Kapitsa... 9 July [O.S. 26 June] 1894 – 8 April 1984) was a leading Soviet Russian physicist and Nobel laureate, whose research focused on low-temperature physics. 

Known for: Superfluidity, Kapitza instability, Kapitza number, Kapitza resistance, Kapitza's pendulum, Kapitsa–Dirac effect. 

Awards: FRS (1929) Faraday Medal (1942) Franklin Medal (1944) Lomonosov Gold Medal (1959) Cothenius Medal (1959) Rutherford Medal and Prize (1966) Nobel Prize in Physics (1978). 

In Russia, Kapitsa began a series of experiments to study liquid helium. This research culminated with the 1937 discovery of superfluidity (another expression of the state of matter that gives rise to superconductivity)... In 1978 Kapitsa won the Nobel Prize in Physics "for his basic inventions and discoveries in the area of low-temperature physics" and was also cited for his long term role as a leader in the development of this area.

Summary: 
Pyotr Kapitsa was a prominent Soviet Russian physicist born in 1894, best known for his pioneering research in low-temperature physics. His major contributions include the discovery of superfluidity in 1937 and the development of techniques for creating liquid helium. He was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1978, alongside numerous other prestigious awards such as the Faraday Medal, Franklin Medal, and Lomonosov Gold Medal. This biographical and professional information provides a comprehensive profile to verify if he matches the specific criteria you are looking for.
