Nikolay Nikolayevich Semyonov ... (Russian: Никола́й Никола́евич Семёнов; 15 April [O.S. 3 April] 1896 – 25 September 1986) was a Soviet physicist and chemist. Semyonov was awarded the 1956 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work on the mechanism of chemical transformation. 
Semyonov was born in Saratov in April 1896, the son of Yelena Dmitrieva and Nikolai Aleksandrovich Semyonov. He graduated from the department of physics of Petrograd University (1913–1917), where he was a student of Abram Fyodorovich Ioffe. 
Semyonov's outstanding work on the mechanism of chemical transformation includes an exhaustive analysis of the application of the chain theory to varied reactions (1934–1954) and, more significantly, to combustion processes. He proposed a theory of degenerate branching, which led to a better understanding of the phenomena associated with the induction periods of oxidation processes. He spent most of his career focusing and developing the field of chemical chain reactions. ... He is the only Soviet/Russian Chemistry Nobel Laureate, who received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry (together with Sir Cyril N. Hinshelwood) for his work in 1956.

Summary: 
Nikolay Semyonov (1896–1986) was a prominent Soviet physicist and chemist. He is best known for his exhaustive work on the mechanism of chemical transformation, specifically involving chain reactions and combustion processes. Notably, he was awarded the 1956 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, making him the only Soviet/Russian to receive the award in this category. These key biographical and professional details provide the necessary context to check if he is the matching person for the user's query.
