Nikoloz (Niko) Muskhelishvili... 16 February [O.S. 4 February] 1891 – 15 July 1976) was a Soviet Georgian mathematician, physicist and engineer who was one of the founders and first President (1941–1972) of the Georgian SSR Academy of Sciences (now Georgian National Academy of Sciences).
Muskhelishvili was born on 16 February [O.S. 4 February] 1891 in Tbilisi, then part of the Russian Empire into a family of engineers. He graduated from local grammar school in 1909 and afterwards from the Physics and Mathematics Faculty of Saint Petersburg in 1914... At request of the short-lived Democratic Republic of Georgia he moved back to his native country in 1920 in order to organize the establishment of a national scientific school. There Muskhelishvili conducted lessons in the Tbilisi State University and Polytechnic Institute as an assistant professor and from 1922 to 1938 as head professor... In 1941 based on the former Georgian Academy of Sciences a new USSR Academy of Sciences was established by the Georgian SSR and Muskhelishvili got elected as its first president and academician.
Muskhelishvili conducted fundamental research on the theories of physical elasticity, Integral equations, Boundary value problems and other. He was one of the first to apply the theory of functions of complex variables to the problems of elasticity theories... His works solved all major problems of the Plane Elasticity Theory opening a wide class of domains reducing the plane problem to finite systems of linear algebraic equations c singular kernels.
During World War II Muskhelishvili was responsible for retargeting the preoccupation of the Academy of Science to national defense. He completed a series of research, experimental and theoretical work in different areas of applied mathematics, physics and mechanics... Muskhelishvili was a renowned specialist in engineering able to apply a lot of his theories and solutions, including torsion bar suspension for tracked vehicles such as tanks.
Notable awards: Hero of Socialist Labour (1945), Stalin Prize (1941), (1947), Order of Lenin (1941), (1945), (1952), (1961), (1966), (1975), Lomonosov Gold Medal (1972).

Summary: 
Nikoloz Muskhelishvili (1891–1976) was a highly influential Soviet Georgian mathematician, physicist, and engineer. He was a key figure in the establishment of the Georgian SSR Academy of Sciences, serving as its first president from 1941 to 1972. Muskhelishvili is renowned for his fundamental research in physical elasticity, integral equations, and boundary value problems, successfully solving all major problems in Plane Elasticity Theory. During World War II, he pivoted his focus to national defense, contributing vital research to military hardware, such as torsion bar suspensions for tanks. His extraordinary contributions earned him prestigious honors, including the Hero of Socialist Labour, Stalin Prize, and multiple Orders of Lenin.
