Dmitry Pavlovich Kostomarov (Russian: Дмитрий Павлович Костомаров; 23 March 1929 – 9 August 2014) was a Soviet and Russian mathematician, academician of the Russian Academy of Sciences, dean of the Faculty of Computational Mathematics and Cybernetics at Moscow State University (1990—1999), Professor, Dr.Sc.

Born into the family of an engineer, a representative of the noble family of the Kostomarovs. In 1948 he transferred to the Faculty of Physics of Moscow State University, which he graduated with honors in 1952.

Fundamental results in the field of mathematical modeling in plasma physics, electrodynamics, nuclear physics. He is the author of 10 monographs and more than 137 research papers.

Awards and honours: Lomonosov Prize of Moscow State University for achievements in the field of science (1976), Honored Worker of Science and Technology of the RSFSR (1980), USSR State Prize (1981), Order of the Red Banner of Labour (1990), Order of Honour (1999), Order of Friendship (2005).

Summary: 
Dmitry Kostomarov (1929–2014) was a notable Soviet and Russian mathematician, academician of the Russian Academy of Sciences, and dean of the Faculty of Computational Mathematics and Cybernetics at Moscow State University. He contributed fundamentally to mathematical modeling in plasma physics, electrodynamics, and nuclear physics, authoring 10 monographs and over 137 research papers. His achievements were recognized with numerous awards, including the USSR State Prize, the Order of the Red Banner of Labour, and the Order of Honour.
