Solomon Grigor'evich Mikhlin (Russian: Соломо́н Григо́рьевич Ми́хлин, real name Zalman Girshevich Mikhlin) (the family name is also transliterated as Mihlin or Michlin) (23 April 1908 – 29 August 1990) was a Soviet mathematician of who worked in the fields of linear elasticity, singular integrals and numerical analysis: he is best known for the introduction of the symbol of a singular integral operator, which eventually led to the foundation and development of the theory of pseudodifferential operators. He was born in Kholmech, Rechytsa District, Minsk Governorate (in present-day Belarus) on 23 April 1908; ... He graduated from a secondary school in Gomel in 1923 and entered the State Herzen Pedagogical Institute in 1925. In 1927 he was transferred to the Department of Mathematics and Mechanics of Leningrad State University as a second year student ... In 1932 he got a position at the Seismological Institute of the USSR Academy of Sciences, where he worked till 1941 ... Since 1944 S.G. Mikhlin has been professor at the Leningrad State University.

Summary: 
